Channels now have policies attached to them. To ease the migration by default new channels are given the "allow all" policy.

Policies limit which events or queries the channel will accept. The policies are defined as simple json maps. For events you define which domains and types are allowed and which are denied. For queries instead of `domain` and `type` you use `rid` and `name`.

For example, a policy that allows all events with domain `foo` and type `bar`. An event `foo/hello` will be rejected. Also all queries will be rejected since the policy didn't define any query rules.
```krl
{
    name: "only allow foo/bar events",
    event: {
        allow: [
            // This is a list of rules.
            // If the event matches one of these rules, the event will be allowed
            {domain: "foo", type: "bar"}
        ]
    }
}
```

Now let's try a policy that will allow all events with domain `foo`, but reject `foo/bar`.
```krl
{
    name: "allow foo/* but deny foo/bar",
    event: {
        allow: [
            {domain: "foo"}// omitting `type` means match all
            {domain: "aaa", type: "bbb"},
        ],
        deny: [
            // deny creates a black list of events
            {domain: "foo", type: "bar"}
        ],
    }
}
// foo/foo - allowed
// foo/wat - allowed
// foo/bar - denied b/c it matches a rule in the `deny` list
// zzz/wat - denied b/c domain zzz is not allowed
// aaa/bbb - allowed b/c it matched an `allow` rule
// aaa/ccc - denied b/c it didn't match an `allow` rule
```

Now let's allow all events except `system/*` and `danger/nuke`
```krl
{
    name: "blacklist system/secret and system/danger",
    event: {
        allow: [
            {}// omitting `domain` and `type` means match all events
        ],
        deny: [
            {domain: "system"},
            {domain: "danger", type: "nuke"},
        ],
    }
}
// foo/bar - allowed
// hello/system - allowed
// system/secret - denied
// system/foobar - denied
// danger/gun - allowed
// danger/nuke - denied
```

Queries work the same. But use `rid`+`name` instead of `domain`+`type`

The allow all policy looks like this
```krl
{
    name: "allow all",
    event: {
        allow: [{}],
    },
    query: {
        allow: [{}],
    }
}
```

To create a policy in the engine:
```krl
engine:newPolicy({
    name: "only allow foo/bar events",
    event: {
        allow: [
            {domain: "foo", type: "bar"}
        ]
    }
})
```

The `engine:newPolicy` function returns the complete policy that includes it's id. So the above newPolicy returns
```krl
{
    id: "1234",
    name: "only allow foo/bar events",
    event: {
        allow: [
            {domain: "foo", type: "bar"}
        ],
        deny: [],
    },
    query: {allow: [], deny: []}
}
```

You can then use that returned id to to create a new channel that adopts that policy. i.e.  `engine:newChannel(... policy_id = "1234")`

You can also `engine:listPolicies()` to see all policies in the engine.

```krl
[
    {id: "1234", name: "policy 1", event: {allow: [...]} query: ...},
    {id: "4321", name: "policy 2", event: {allow: [...]} query: ...},
    {id: "5555", name: "policy 3", event: {allow: [...]} query: ...},
]
```

To delete a policy use `engine:removePolicy(policy_id)` It only works if the policy is not in use by any channels.


